shorts_description:
Here are the top 5 anti inflammatory foods you should eat regularly! These foods are packed with antioxidants, which have been shown to reduce oxidative stress in the body and fight inflammation. As you may know, inflammation is your body's way of defending itself against infection or injury. It's what makes your muscles sore after a workout and helps your body heal when you have a cut on your finger. 

But when inflammation goes unchecked, it can lead to chronic diseases like arthritis, heart disease, diabetes and more. So what can you do about it? Eating an anti inflammatory diet can help keep your body in check by preventing oxidative stress from damaging cells.

Today's Cybersecurity Lesson: Don't plug in random thumb drives

Picture this: you find a thumb drive in a parking lot, and it says SPACEX on it. You‚Äôre dying of curiosity. It might contain the plans for the first city on Mars! 
Don‚Äôt. Don‚Äôt do it. Just walk away! 

NEVER plug in a USB flash drive that you find out in the wild. You don‚Äôt know what could be on it!  Malware from a hacker, or worse, a ‚ÄúUSB Killer‚Äù that contains a capacitor that stores up a charge and then discharges it, killing your hardware. 

But what about those lovely free thumbdrives you‚Äôre getting in swag bags at conferences? 
Forget it. They‚Äôre not worth it. Instead, buy yourself a nice clean SSD drive.

Rory Sutherland tells how using a simple marketing trick they made their letters important to clients and why banks are building their buildings so massive and beautiful.

Rory Sutherland brilliantly demonstrates the impact of perceived value in marketing by recounting how they transformed a simple communication into something that commanded attention. Typically, companies send out emails or standard mail to convey information, but these can easily be ignored or dismissed. Instead of following this predictable route, Sutherland and his team employed a clever strategy: they started sending otherwise generic letters through FedEx and UPS. This added a tangible layer of significance to each message, conveying to the recipient that the content must be important if the company invested in a premium delivery service.

This approach leverages the psychology of perceived effort and cost. When someone receives a letter through FedEx or UPS, they instinctively sense that extra resources‚Äîtime, money, and intention‚Äîwere spent to ensure the message arrived safely and promptly. This perceived investment immediately elevates the letter‚Äôs importance, leading the recipient to open it with more curiosity and respect. Unlike a regular email or letter that blends into the background noise, these express-delivered messages stand out and are harder to ignore.

Sutherland‚Äôs story underscores how a relatively small investment in presentation can dramatically shift a customer‚Äôs perception, elevating what might otherwise be routine information to something valuable. This technique goes beyond the physical realm‚Äîit shows the power of signaling importance through action rather than words, a core principle that can be applied to various aspects of marketing, from packaging to customer service. It‚Äôs a simple yet powerful reminder that in a world where convenience often wins, taking the extra step to convey value can make all the difference in how a brand is perceived and how messages are received.
